        <h1>Passive versus Active Learning</h1>
        <p>Passive lecturing is a mode of teaching used by most instructors at the college level. In this style of teaching, students play a non-active role in the classroom setting as they learn. Typically, the professor presents the material through lecture or visual presentation while students listen and take notes on the given information.</p>
        <p>Issues with passive learning arise when students are not engaged in the lecture material. Lack of engagement prevents the development of critical thinking and problem solving abilities. While this is in no way the fault of the professor, it does affect both the quantity and quality of education.</p>
        <p>Interactive learning, on the other hand, increases the quality of education because the material can be applied through critical thinking. Active learning gives students a chance to have dialogue with others. It also provides them the opportunity to think about the information on their own because they are actively participating in the learning process. “Hands on” discussions help information make the transition to long-term memory. Since passive learning has no two-way exchange, some cannot successfully retain the information. </p>

        <h1>Social Networking Supports Active Learning</h1>
        <p>Students and faculty alike have had their world defined by the Internet for more than a decade. The proliferation of digital, social and mobile technologies has created a culture in which we participate more in creating and sharing content. As a result, the way we communicate, interact, and learn has profoundly changed. In today’s world, students are accustomed to an interactive society. At the core of this transformation are social networking technologies, such as Facebook and Twitter, which are blurring the lines between our professional, personal, and academic lives.</p>
        <p>Unlike Facebook and Twitter, niche social networks are valuable because of their ability to build committed communities where individuals support each other in the pursuit of common goals. Academically-organized social networking technologies can complement the lecture and help engage a student’s interest, attention, and level of interaction. These student-centered and instructor-facilitated communities are available synchronous or asynchronous, via any location, and through the use of mobile and non-mobile devices. </p>

        <h1>Help Reform Higher Education!</h1>
        <p>Current topics of postsecondary debate include accountability-driven questions about the cost and quality of higher education. Furthermore, there is a broad consensus that the long-term key to continued U.S. competitiveness in a global economy is the adequacy of supply and quality of the workforce; student retention and postsecondary completion have recently emerged as leading concerns of the Obama Administration, the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, and the Lumina Foundation.</p>
        <p>The productivity and efficiency prospects offered by the information-technology revolution have exciting potential to help reform higher education. Most universities, however, view Web 2.0 technologies in education as simply curriculum-delivery devices. The widely-used course or learning management systems are great tools to help instructors deliver course announcements and links to course resources, as well as to organize grades and assignments. Unfortunately, <strong>learning management systems do not encourage student engagement or active learning.</strong></p>
        <p>Very few instructors have adopted social media to create engaging online environments to complement their lecture because the main social media platforms, Facebook and Twitter, are primarily used as non-academic social tools. WikiGrads is a social learning platform that provides active discussion/Q & A forums for university courses, individually and in groups. Complementation of online forums driven by social networking technologies with traditional lectures promises to increase the quality of the learning experience and student engagement, thereby improving student retention and success.</p>

